Tyding Data in R

R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

summary(cars)
##      speed           dist       
##  Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
##  1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00  
##  Median :15.0   Median : 36.00  
##  Mean   :15.4   Mean   : 42.98  
##  3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
##  Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00

Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

Read in data from [https://knb.ecoinformatics.org](catch_df <- read.csv(url(“https://knb.ecoinformatics.org/knb/d1/mn/v2/object/df35b.302.1”),

catch_url <- read.csv(url("https://knb.ecoinformatics.org/knb/d1/mn/v2/object/df35b.302.1", method = "libcurl"), stringsAsFactors = F)
                                      
        
head(catch_url)                             
##   Region Year Chinook Sockeye Coho Pink Chum All notesRegCode
## 1    SSE 1886       0       5    0    0    0   5             
## 2    SSE 1887       0     155    0    0    0 155             
## 3    SSE 1888       0     224   16    0    0 240             
## 4    SSE 1889       0     182   11   92    0 285             
## 5    SSE 1890       0     251   42    0    0 292             
## 6    SSE 1891       0     274   24    0    0 298
catch_df <- catch_url %>% 
select(-All, -notesRegCode)
# select positively by name
# select(Region, Year, Chinook,...)
